	<div align="center" class="main-content">
		<div class="spacer">
	</div><br>			<label class="collapse_ACT" for="_1"><font size="5px">NikR transcriptional activity</font></label>
				<input id="_1" type="checkbox">
				<div class="ACT"><br><ul><li>Typhimurium NikR is not known and , importantly , it is not known how this organism imports nickel for its hydrogenase activity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21722794" target="_blank">21722794</a>]<br></li>
<li>NikR is anticipated to sense nickel although its target genes in S. enterica sv .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21722794" target="_blank">21722794</a>]<br></li>
<li>It remains to be established to what extent this is coordinated with the NikR and Fur mediated regulation in this organism lacking the NikABCDE nickel uptake system .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21722794" target="_blank">21722794</a>]<br></li>
<li>Furthermore , at low extracellular nickel levels , low or transient expression of RcnA is required to prevent premature nikABCDE repression by NikR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21722794" target="_blank">21722794</a>]<br></li>
<li>This is proposed to result from competition between nickel efflux by RcnA and nickel binding and transcriptional repression by NikR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21722794" target="_blank">21722794</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although NikR can bind a variety of metals , it has been proposed that only nickel binding at these sites can induce the appropriate conformational change in NikR for DNA-binding ( Wang et al. , 2009 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21722794" target="_blank">21722794</a>]<br></li>
<li>NikR also responds to lower nickel concentrations than RcnR , such that as cytosolic nickel levels increase , NikR detects these metals and prevents import via NikABCDE , whereas only when a higher threshold of these metals is reached does RcnR detect these metals and trigger export by RcnA preventing excess metal accumulation in the cell .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21722794" target="_blank">21722794</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_DOM" for="_2"><font size="5px">NikR protein domains</font></label>
				<input id="_2" type="checkbox">
				<div class="DOM"><br><ul><li>Crystal structure of the nickel-responsive transcription factor NikR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21722794" target="_blank">21722794</a>]<br></li>
<li>Two amino-terminal DNA-binding motifs of a NikR dimer intertwine to form a ribbon -- helix -- helix DNA-binding domain , and two NikR dimers form a tetrameric complex .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21722794" target="_blank">21722794</a>]<br></li>
<li>The NikR tetramer has four identical carboxyl-terminal high affinity nickel-binding sites , 1 per monomer , at the central tetrameric interface , flanked by the two DNA-binding domains ( Schreiter et al. , 2003 , 2006 ; Phillips et al. , 2008 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21722794" target="_blank">21722794</a>]<br></li>
<li>The structure of a DNA-bound NikR complex has also revealed two potassium ions in sites bridging the metal - and DNA-binding domains ( Schreiter et al. , 2006 ) , which are also suggested to play a structural role in the protein-DNA complex ( Wang et al. , 2009 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21722794" target="_blank">21722794</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_EVO" for="_3"><font size="5px">NikR evolution</font></label>
				<input id="_3" type="checkbox">
				<div class="EVO"><br><ul><li>Transcriptional Regulation by NikR The E. coli NikR ( 99 % identity over 133 amino acids to the S. enterica sv .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21722794" target="_blank">21722794</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
